<Window x:Class="TotoriColeCheat.MainWindow"
        xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml/presentation"
        xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml"
        xmlns:d="http://schemas.microsoft.com/expression/blend/2008"
        xmlns:mc="http://schemas.openxmlformats.org/markup-compatibility/2006"
        xmlns:local="clr-namespace:TotoriColeCheat"
        mc:Ignorable="d"
        Title="Atelier Totori tool for changing your Cole value to 400,000 or 600,000." Height="506" Width="806">
    <Grid Height="460" VerticalAlignment="Top">
        <Grid.ColumnDefinitions>
            <ColumnDefinition/>
        </Grid.ColumnDefinitions>
        <RadioButton x:Name="radiobutton_600k" Content="600,000 Cole" HorizontalAlignment="Left" Margin="77,432,0,0" Width="110" IsChecked="True" RenderTransformOrigin="0.585,4.763" Height="22" VerticalAlignment="Top"/>
        <RadioButton x:Name="radiobutton_400k" Content="400,000 Cole&#xD;&#xA;" Margin="232,432,466,0" VerticalAlignment="Top" RenderTransformOrigin="-0.024,0.562" Height="31"/>
        <TextBlock Margin="10,10,19,0" TextWrapping="Wrap" VerticalAlignment="Top" Height="411"><Run Text="Reasonings:"/><LineBreak/><Run/><LineBreak/><Run Text="1. The amount of effort it takes to get 500,000 for a certain ending"/><LineBreak/><Run Text="2. The recommended methods that many community members on GameFaqs recommend end up hurting some of the game's enjoyment and/or make this game feel more like a job"/><LineBreak/><Run Text="3. On loop #2, just starting out with 40k-80k is more than enough to change how the game is played. I don't feel much more than that makes a difference"/><LineBreak/><Run Text="4. 600,000 Cole should be enough to have some money to enjoy playing. I do recommend beating at least 1-2 loops before using this cheat"/><LineBreak/><Run Text="5. The 400,000 Cole setting is if you still want to do some work to get there"/><LineBreak/><Run Text="6. I don't think any value above 600,000 would affect gameplay in a way that makes the experience dramatically different"/><LineBreak/><Run/><LineBreak/><Run Text="Instructions"/><LineBreak/><Run/><LineBreak/><Run Text="1. Find your Steam UserData folder. Find your Steam ID under that, and Atelier Totori should be 936180 (thanks to pcgamingwiki for this information). It often is C:\program files (x86)\Steam\UserData\(your steam id)\936180 or C:\program files\Steam\UserData\(your steam id)\936180 . Source: https://www.pcgamingwiki.com/wiki/Atelier_Totori:_The_Adventurer_of_Arland_DX"/><LineBreak/><Run Text="2. Start the game"/><LineBreak/><Run Text="3. Load any saved game "/><LineBreak/><Run Text="3. Come back to this tool"/><LineBreak/><Run Text="4. Pick the save game # you want. Make sure to not use your main saved game (in other words, make a duplicate save on the game you want to modify)"/><LineBreak/><Run Text="5. Load the modified save game #"/><LineBreak/><Run/><LineBreak/><Run Text="You may have to disable Steam cloud saving in order for this to work, but I did not have to using this trick. This software is open source and comes with no warranty. I pretty much threw it together in maybe 30 minutes or so. Enjoy!"/></TextBlock>
        <Button Content="Modify Your Save!" HorizontalAlignment="Left" Margin="544,426,0,0" Width="136" Click="Button_Click" Height="28" VerticalAlignment="Top"/>

    </Grid>
</Window>
